agedy -- tCHAPTER 25. The Tragic Case of Capital Punishment -- tCHAPTER 26. Constitutional Tragedies: The Dark Side of Judgment -- tCHAPTER 27. Good Constitutions and Bad Choices -- tCHAPTER 28. Jocasta Undone -- tCHAPTER 29. Constitutional Tragedy in Dying: Or Whose Tragedy Is It, Anyway? -- tCHAPTER 30. Dramatic Jurisprudence -- tCHAPTER 31. Constitutional Farce -- tCHAPTER 32. Constitutional Merry-Go-Round -- tCHAPTER 33. Glamis, Yes; Cawdor, Yes— but King of Scotland? -- tCHAPTER 34. Brown v. Board of Education -- tCHAPTER 35. Tragedy and Constitutional Interpretation -- tCHAPTER 36. The Meaning of Blacks7 Fidelity to the Constitution -- tCHAPTER 37. Tragedies under the Common Law Constitution -- tCHAPTER 38. McCulloch v. Maryland -- tCHAPTER 39. Antigone and Creon -- tAPPENDIX. The Constitution of the United States -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Constitution is the cornerstone of American government, hailed as one of the greatest contributions of the Western Enlightenment. While many seem content simply to celebrate it, those most familiar with the document invariably find it wanting in at least some aspects. This unique volume brings together many of the country's most esteemed constitutional commentators and invites them to answer two questions: First, what is the stupidest provision of the Constitution? "Stupid" need not mean evil. Thus, a second, related question is whether the scholar-interpreter would be forced to reach truly evil results even if applying his or her own favored theory of constitutional interpretation. The contributors include Lawrence Alexander, Akhil Reed Amar, Jack Balkin, Philip Bobbitt, Gerard Bradley, Rebecca Brown, Steven Calabresi, Lief Carter, Christopher Eisgruber, Lawrence Sager, Marie Failinger, Daniel Farber, James Fleming, Mark Graber, Stephen Griffin, Gary Jacobsohn, Randall Kennedy, Lewis L